Thanks for this update.
I have a couple of comments/suggestions:

I've just done some reading about comments in the Python code and discovered that it's normally not recommended to use string literals as comments. The main arguments are that it's not standard and that there could be some side effects. So, could you please replace the string literals with # prefixed comments?
I think that the python sub-directory is one sub-directory too much :-) I'd prefer to keep all the clients in one directory called clients. If, one day, there are too many clients in this directory, then we'll move it to a separate GitHub repository.
I think that it would be better to keep TX and RX clients in separate files.

Out of curiosity, I've found the code in the Linux kernel that works with scripts:
https://github.com/Xilinx/linux-xlnx/blob/xilinx-v2016.4/fs/binfmt_script.c

column21:
searching internet for random examples to prove your right?
Your also quoting unix and not Linux sources.
Simply put Debian isn't unix, bash on ubuntu isn't parsing the script as proper bash and not allowing things like arithmetic in for loops correctly with the space. Remove the space things work.

column13: #!/bin/bash shebang line correction
column20: the bash interpretation is not properly handling items because of this extra space
column21:
Your also quoting unix and not Linux sources.

The link from my previous comment is the latest Linux version provided by Xilinx:
https://github.com/Xilinx/linux-xlnx/blob/xilinx-v2016.4/fs/binfmt_script.c#L57
Basically, it's exactly the Linux version running on Red Pitaya.

bash on ubuntu isn't parsing the script as proper bash and not allowing things like arithmetic in for loops correctly with the space

Then this isn't the problem of the extra spaces but of the interpreter command. The patch should replace #! /bin/sh with #! /bin/bash.
I've just tested that bash arithmetic in for loops works with #! /bin/bash and with #!/bin/bash but it doesn't work with #! /bin/sh nor with #!/bin/sh. Here is my test script:
#! /bin/bash

for i in {1..3}
do
   for j in {1..3}
   do
       echo "scale = 3; sqrt($i*$i + $j*$j)" | bc
   done
done

Patch for opt_design errors due to trimming of unused paths
column20:
In some conditions the status register core causes opt_design errors like this one:

[Opt 31-67] Problem: A LUT3 cell in the design is missing a connection on input pin I0, which is used by the LUT equation. This pin has either been left unconnected in the design or the connection was removed due to the trimming of unused logic. The LUT cell name is: system_i/axi_interconnect_0/xbar/inst/gen_sasd.crossbar_sasd_0/s_axi_bresp[1]_INST_0.

This happens due to undriven LUTs which are removed in opt_design. The error does not happen in every design and I could not reproduce it. It seems to be rooted deep in the mysteries of the optimization algorithm. The core is working without (known) issues if the commited lines are appended to the code.

Enhance AXIS_RAM_WRITER by adding a total counter
column20: We extended the axis_ram_writer to keep track of the total number of samples written. This is quite convenient in a client server setting, where the client only reads partial data. Then, even if the ram overflows, one can determine the total sample number. This is my first time I touch verilog code. So apologies if there are things wrong, or if the naming is not perfect. I tested it and it seems to work.

The counter functionality can be easily implemented as a separate module. For example, I have a similar module that also counts the incoming data samples:
https://github.com/pavel-demin/red-pitaya-notes/tree/master/cores/axis_packetizer_v1_0

maybe use the same address for the reset signal in all the applications (for example 0x40040000)
maybe use the same address for the FIFO reader in all the applications (for example 0x40041000)
maybe make it a separate Tcl file that can be reused in all applications
